0:["Tb5vTC4GbBfflsZ6cs9ht",[[["",{"children":["articles",{"children":[["slug","push-up-progressions","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__?{\"slug\":\"push-up-progressions\"}",{}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["articles",{"children":[["slug","push-up-progressions","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",[["$","$L2",null,{"article":{"slug":"push-up-progressions","category":"guides","tag":"Training Guide","title":"The Complete Push-Up Progression: From Zero to One-Arm","subtitle":"A step-by-step framework for building elite pushing strength using nothing but your bodyweight and a floor.","excerpt":"A step-by-step system for building elite upper-body strength using only your bodyweight. No bench, no bars, no excuses.","author":"Sarah Okafor","authorBio":"Sarah Okafor is a certified strength & conditioning specialist (CSCS) with 11 years of experience coaching bodyweight athletes. She has trained over 400 clients to their first one-arm push-up.","date":"Feb 14, 2026","readTime":"12 min","image":"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1571019614242-c5c5dee9f50b?w=1200&q=85&fit=crop","featured":true,"content":[{"type":"intro","text":"The push-up is the most underestimated exercise in existence. In gyms everywhere, it gets dismissed as a warmup drill — something you do before the \"real\" work. That perception is completely wrong. Mastered properly, the push-up is a full-chain pressing movement that builds chest, shoulders, triceps, core, and even lat engagement. And unlike the bench press, it travels with you."},{"type":"body","text":"This guide covers every level of the push-up progression — from your first wall push-up to the one-arm variant that most gym veterans can't achieve. Each step has specific benchmarks. Don't skip ahead. The athletes who try to rush the progression are the same ones who plateau at 20 reps and wonder why they've been stuck there for three years."},{"type":"pullquote","text":"The athletes who rush the progression plateau at 20 reps and wonder why they've been stuck there for years."},{"type":"h2","text":"Why the Push-Up Is Harder Than It Looks"},{"type":"body","text":"A standard push-up moves roughly 69% of your bodyweight. For a 180 lb person, that's 124 lbs loaded through your chest, shoulders, and triceps on every single rep. A 45 lb barbell bench press is, by comparison, a warmup. The issue most people face isn't strength — it's positioning. Bad push-up form turns a full-body exercise into a lower back destruction machine."},{"type":"tip","text":"The \"plank with arms\" cue is your foundation. Before any push-up variation, set your plank: neutral spine, glutes engaged, core braced, hands slightly wider than shoulders. If you can't hold this for 60 seconds, spend a week there before moving on."},{"type":"h2","text":"The 6-Level Progression"},{"type":"body","text":"Each level has a mastery benchmark. Reach it before advancing. If you're honest about your level, this progression will take most people 3–6 months start to finish. It took me 14 months to reach Level 6. Take your time."},{"type":"h3","text":"Level 1 — Incline Push-Up"},{"type":"exercise","text":"Incline Push-Up","level":"Beginner","sets":"3","reps":"10–15","note":"Use a kitchen counter, desk, or sturdy box. The higher the surface, the easier the movement. Work toward a surface at hip height, then progress to knee height. Master 3×15 at knee height before moving to Level 2."},{"type":"body","text":"The incline push-up is not a cop-out. It's a precision tool for learning the movement pattern without the load. Focus entirely on form here: elbows at 45° to your torso (not flared, not pinned), straight line from head to heel, controlled descent over 2–3 seconds."},{"type":"h3","text":"Level 2 — Knee Push-Up (The Right Way)"},{"type":"exercise","text":"Modified Knee Push-Up","level":"Beginner+","sets":"3","reps":"12–20","note":"Cross your ankles, don't let your hips sag or pike. Your body should still form a straight diagonal from knees to shoulders. Mastery benchmark: 3×20 with a 2-second descent and 1-second pause at the bottom."},{"type":"h3","text":"Level 3 — Full Push-Up"},{"type":"exercise","text":"Standard Push-Up","level":"Intermediate","sets":"4","reps":"8–15","note":"If you can't do 5 strict reps, go back to Level 2. \"Strict\" means: full range of motion (chest within an inch of the floor), zero hip sag, elbows tracking at 45°. Mastery benchmark: 4×15 with perfect form."},{"type":"pullquote","text":"\"Strict\" means chest within an inch of the floor, zero hip sag, elbows tracking at 45°. Anything else is a partial rep."},{"type":"h3","text":"Level 4 — Archer Push-Up"},{"type":"exercise","text":"Archer Push-Up","level":"Intermediate+","sets":"4","reps":"6–10 per side","note":"Widen your hand placement significantly. As you lower, shift your weight to one arm while the opposite arm extends straight. This is the unilateral bridge between the standard push-up and the one-arm. Mastery benchmark: 4×8 per side, controlled."},{"type":"body","text":"The archer push-up is where most people get humbled. The lateral shift demands far more from your wrists, forearms, and stabilizers than any standard variation. Expect soreness in places you didn't know existed."},{"type":"h3","text":"Level 5 — Assisted One-Arm Push-Up"},{"type":"exercise","text":"Assisted One-Arm Push-Up","level":"Advanced","sets":"4","reps":"5–8 per side","note":"Place your working hand on the floor, supporting hand on a slightly elevated surface (a book, a yoga block). Gradually lower the support height over weeks. This is where elbow alignment becomes critical — the working elbow must track directly over the wrist. Mastery benchmark: 4×6 with support no higher than 4 inches."},{"type":"tip","text":"Wrist strength is often the limiting factor at this level, not pushing power. Supplement your training with 2 minutes of daily wrist circles, loaded wrist extensions, and fingertip push-ups on soft surfaces."},{"type":"h3","text":"Level 6 — One-Arm Push-Up"},{"type":"exercise","text":"One-Arm Push-Up","level":"Elite","sets":"3","reps":"3–5 per side","note":"Feet slightly wider than shoulder width for stability. Free hand behind your back or at your side. Full range of motion — chest must touch or nearly touch the floor. Do not let your hips rotate. The body stays square. There are no shortcuts here."},{"type":"image","src":"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1598971639058-fab3c3109a46?w=900&q=85&fit=crop","caption":"The archer push-up is the critical bridge between bilateral and unilateral pressing strength."},{"type":"h2","text":"Programming It Into Your Week"},{"type":"body","text":"Push-up progressions respond best to frequency over volume. Three sessions per week, with 48 hours between, gives you more practice reps than a single high-volume day while allowing full recovery. Each session should include your current working level (4 sets) plus the level below as a warmup (2 sets, easy)."},{"type":"list","items":["Monday: 2×10 warm-up (previous level) + 4×max at current level","Wednesday: 2×10 warm-up + 4×max at current level + 1×max at next level (practice)","Friday: Full session at current level — aim for a PR on your final set","Never train push-ups on consecutive days — recovery is part of the program","When you can comfortably exceed the mastery benchmark, advance to the next level"]},{"type":"pullquote","text":"Three sessions per week with 48 hours between gives you more practice reps than any single high-volume day while allowing full recovery."},{"type":"h2","text":"Common Mistakes That Kill Progress"},{"type":"body","text":"After coaching hundreds of people through this progression, the failure modes are completely predictable. Here are the ones I see constantly."},{"type":"list","items":["Partial reps: If you're not going chest-to-floor, you're not building the bottom-range strength you need for advanced variations","Flared elbows: This is how you earn a shoulder impingement. 45° angle is not optional","Skipping levels: The archer push-up exists for a reason. It's not optional on the way to a one-arm","Rushing: Most athletes spend 3–4 weeks at each level. That's not a sign of weakness — it's how strength works","Ignoring wrist prep: Wrist flexibility and strength will become the bottleneck. Address it proactively"]},{"type":"h2","text":"A Note on Why This Actually Works"},{"type":"body","text":"Push-up progressions work because they follow the principle of progressive overload in the most honest way possible: you add load by changing your leverage, not by adding plates. When you shift from a standard push-up to an archer push-up, you're increasing the demand on your target muscles by redistributing your bodyweight. It's physics, not gimmickry."},{"type":"body","text":"The one-arm push-up is not a party trick. It requires and builds extraordinary unilateral strength, core anti-rotation stability, wrist tendon integrity, and shoulder stability. Athletes who can perform 5 clean one-arm push-ups on each side will have chest and shoulder strength that competes with anyone pressing twice their bodyweight on a bar."},{"type":"tip","text":"Track every session. Write down your sets, reps, and any notes on form breakdown. The athletes who keep training logs progress twice as fast as those who wing it. This is not an opinion — it's an observation made over a decade of coaching."}]},"related":[{"slug":"silent-hiit-science","category":"guides","tag":"Science & Training","title":"The Science Behind Low-Impact HIIT (And Why It Works)","excerpt":"High-intensity training without the jumping. How to keep heart rate elevated, protect your joints, and not anger your downstairs neighbor.","author":"Dr. Priya Nair","date":"Jan 30, 2026","readTime":"8 min","image":"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552674605-db6ffd4facb5?w=600&q=80&fit=crop"},{"slug":"mobility-desk-workers","category":"guides","tag":"Mobility","title":"The 15-Minute Mobility Routine Every Desk Worker Needs","excerpt":"Sitting 8 hours a day wrecks your hips, thoracic spine, and shoulders. This daily sequence undoes the damage in 15 minutes.","author":"Sarah Okafor","date":"Dec 19, 2025","readTime":"6 min","image":"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544367567-0f2fcb009e0b?w=600&q=80&fit=crop"}]}],["$","$L3",null,{}]]],null],null]},["$","$L4",null,{"parallelRouterKey":"children","segmentPath":["children","articles","children","$5","children"],"error":"$undefined","errorStyles":"$undefined","errorScripts":"$undefined","template":["$","$L6",null,{}],"templateStyles":"$undefined","templateScripts":"$undefined","notFound":"$undefined","notFoundStyles":"$undefined","styles":null}],null]},["$","$L4",null,{"parallelRouterKey":"children","segmentPath":["children","articles","children"],"error":"$undefined","errorStyles":"$undefined","errorScripts":"$undefined","template":["$","$L6",null,{}],"templateStyles":"$undefined","templateScripts":"$undefined","notFound":"$undefined","notFoundStyles":"$undefined","styles":null}],null]},[["$","html",null,{"lang":"en","children":["$","body",null,{"className":"__variable_d758cf __variable_dea962 __variable_d501d1","children":["$","$L7",null,{"children":["$","$L8",null,{"children":["$","$L4",null,{"parallelRouterKey":"children","segmentPath":["children"],"error":"$undefined","errorStyles":"$undefined","errorScripts":"$undefined","template":["$","$L6",null,{}],"templateStyles":"$undefined","templateScripts":"$undefined","notFound":[["$","title",null,{"children":"404: This page could not be found."}],["$","div",null,{"style":{"fontFamily":"system-ui,\"Segoe UI\",Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif,\"Apple Color Emoji\",\"Segoe UI Emoji\"","height":"100vh","textAlign":"center","display":"flex","flexDirection":"column","alignItems":"center","justifyContent":"center"},"children":["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","style",null,{"dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"body{color:#000;background:#fff;margin:0}.next-error-h1{border-right:1px solid rgba(0,0,0,.3)}@media (prefers-color-scheme:dark){body{color:#fff;background:#000}.next-error-h1{border-right:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.3)}}"}}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"next-error-h1","style":{"display":"inline-block","margin":"0 20px 0 0","padding":"0 23px 0 0","fontSize":24,"fontWeight":500,"verticalAlign":"top","lineHeight":"49px"},"children":"404"}],["$","div",null,{"style":{"display":"inline-block"},"children":["$","h2",null,{"style":{"fontSize":14,"fontWeight":400,"lineHeight":"49px","margin":0},"children":"This page could not be found."}]}]]}]}]],"notFoundStyles":[],"styles":null}]}]}]}]}],null],null],[[["$","link","0",{"rel":"stylesheet","href":"/_next/static/css/ff665c3c3b7e6e89.css","precedence":"next","crossOrigin":"$undefined"}]],"$L9"]]]]
